column6: Are you the primary caregiver for YOUR STUDY PARTNER, who needs extra assistance due to a disability, condition, or illness? We define a primary caregiver as the person who is primarily responsible for helping make medical care decisions, is emotionally invested in the person's care, and provides help with daily activities (almost daily). Daily caregiving activities may include helping with medical or therapeutic treatment, preparing meal, and/or helping with dressing and/or bathing. Caregivers may be caring for a loved with dementia, or be the parent to a child with development delays or burdensome health conditions, for example.

NL - Does the participant have a significant neurologic disease such as Parkinson's disease, multi-infarct dementia, Huntington's disease, normal pressure hydrocephalus, brain tumor, progressive supranuclear palsy, seizure disorder, subdural hematoma, multiple sclerosis, or history of significant head trauma followed by persistent neurologic defaults or known structural brain abnormalities.
MCI - Does the participant have a significant neurologic disease other than suspected incipient Alzheimer's disease such as...
AD - Does the participant have a significant neurologic disease other than Alzheimer's disease including...

2. Does the participant's screening/baseline MRI scans have evidence of infection, infarction, or other focal lesions?  Participants with multiple lacunes or lacunes in a critical memory structure are excluded.
3. Does the participant have a pacemaker, aneurysm clips, artificial heart valves, ear implants, metal fragments or foreign objects in the eyes, skin or body.

4. NL - Has the participant had major depression or bipolar disorder as described in DSM-IV within the past year or a history of schizophrenia (DSM IV criteria)?
MCI/AD - Does the participant have a history of major depression...or a history of psychotic features, agitation, or behavioral problems within the last 3 months which could lead to difficulty complying with the protocol?
6. Does the participant have a significant systemic illness or unstable medical condition which could lead to difficulty complying with the protocol?
7. Does the participant have any clinically significant abnormalities in B12, RPR, or TFTs that might interfere with the study.
8. Does the participant reside in a skilled nursing facility?
9. Is the participant currently taking, or has he/she taken in the last 4 weeks, any excluded medication(s) as described in the Procedures Manual?
10. Has the participant used another investigational agent within one month prior to screening?

2. NL - Is participant free of memory complaints, verified by an informant, aside from those normal with age?
MCI - Does the subject have memory complaints and memory difficulties that are verified by an informant?
AD - Does the subject have memory complaints that are verified by an informant?

3. NL - Normal memory function documented by scoring at specific cutoffs on the Logical Memory II subscale (delayed Paragraph Recall) from the Wechsler Memory Scaled - Revised (the maximum score is 25)
MCI/AD - Abnormal memory function documented by scoring below the educationn adjusted cutoff on the Logical Memory II subscale (Delayed Paragraph Recall) from the Wechsler Memory Scale - Revised (the maximum score is 25)

4. NL/MCI - Does the participant have Mini-Mental State Exam score between 24 and 30 (inclusive)? (Exceptions must be made for subjects with less than 8 years of education at the discretion of the project director).
AD - Does the participant have an MMSE score between 20 and 26 (inclusive)?

5. NL - Does the participant have a Clinical Dementia Rating of 0? Memory Box score must be 0.
MCI - Does the participant have a Clinical Dementia Rating of 0.5? Memory Box score must be at least 0.5.
AD - Does participant have a Clinical Dementia rating of 0.5 or 1.0?

6. NL - Is the participant cognitively normal based on an absence of significant impairment in cognitive functions or activities of daily living?
MCI - Is the participant's general cognition and functional performance sufficiently perserved such that a diagnosis of Alzheimer's disease cannot be made by the site physician at the time of the screening visit?
AD - Does the participant meet NINCDS/ADRDA criteria for probable AD?
7. Does the participant have a Modified Hachinski score less than or equal to 4?
8. Is the participant between 55 and 90 years of age inclusive?
9. Has the participant been on stable doses of non-excluded medications for at least 4 weeks prior to screening?
10. Does the participant have a Geriatric Depression Scale score of <6?

11. Does the participant have an informant available who they have frequent contact with (e.g. an average of 10 hours per week or more), and can accompany the participant to all clinic visits and imaging sessions for the duration of the protocol?
12. Does the participant have adequate visual and auditory acuity to allow neuropsychological testing?
13. Is the participant in good general health with no additional diseases expected to interfere with the study?
14. If female, is the participant not pregnant, lactating, or of childbearing potential (i.e. women must be two years post-menopausal or surgically sterile)?
17. Has the participant completed 6 grades of education (or had a good work history sufficient to exclude mental retardation)?
18. Is the participant fluent in English or Spanish?

1. Does {P} believe that he/she is in danger - that others are planning to hurt him/her?
2. Does {P} believe that others are stealing from him/her?
3. Does {P} believe that his/her spouse is having an affair?
4. Does {P} believe that unwelcome guests are living in his/her house?
5. Does {P} believe that his/her spouse or others are not who they claim to be?
6. Does {P} believe that his/her house is not his/her home?
7. Does {P} believe that family members plan to abandon him/her?
8. Does {P} believe that television or magazine figures are actually present in the home?  [Does he/she try to talk to or interact with them?]
9. Does {P} believe any other unusual things that I haven't asked about?
1. Does {P} describe hearing voices or act as if he/she hears voices?
2. Does {P} talk to people who are not there?
3. Does {P} describe seeing things not seen by others or behave as if he/she is seeing things not seen by others (people, animals, lights, etc.)?
4. Does {P} report smelling odors not smelled by others?
5. Does {P} describe feeling things on his/her skin or otherwise appear to be feeling things crawling or touching him/her?
6. Does {P} describe tastes that are without any known cause?
7. Does {P} describe any other unusual sensory experiences?
1. Does {P} get upset with those trying to care for him/her or resist activities such as bathing or changing clothes?
2. Is {P} stubborn, having to have things his/her way?
3. Is {P} uncooperative, resistive to help from others?
4. Does {P} have any other behaviors that make him/her hard to handle?
6. Does {P} slam doors, kick furniture, throw things?
7. Does {P} attempt to hurt or hit others?
8. Does {P} have any other aggressive or agitated behaviors?
1. Does {P} have periods of tearfulness or sobbing that seem to indicate sadness?
2. Does {P} say or act as if he/she is sad or low in spirits?
3. Does {P} put him/herself down or say that he/she feels like a failure?
4. Does {P} say that he/she is a bad person or deserves to be punished?
5. Does {P} seem very discouraged or say that he/ she has not future?
6. Does {P} say he/she is a burden to the family or that the family would be better off without him/her?
7. Does {P} express a wish for death or talk about killing him/herself?
8. Does {P} show any other signs of depression or sadness?
1. Does {P} say that he/she is worried about planned events?
2. Does {P} have periods of feeling shaky, unable to relax, or feeling excessively tense?
3. Does {P} have periods of [or complain of] shortness of breath, gasping, or sighing for no apparent reason other than nervousness?
4. Does {P} complain of butterflies in his/her stomach, or of racing or pounding of the heart in association with nervousness? [Symptoms not explained by ill health]?
5. Does {P} avoid certain places or situations that make him.her more nervous such as riding in the car, meeting with friends, or being in crowds?
6. Does {P} become nervous or upset when separated from you [or his/her caregiver]? [Does he/she cling to you to keep from being separated?]
7. Does {P} show any other signs of anxiety?
1. Does {P} appear to feel too good or too happy, different from his/her usual self?
2. Does {P} find humor and laugh at things that others do not find funny?
3. Does {P} seem to have a childish sense of humor with a tendency to giggle or laugh inappropriately (such as when something unfortunate happens to others)?
4. Does {P} tell jokes or make remarks that have little humor for others but seem funny to him/her?
5. Does he/she play childish pranks such as pinching or playing 'keep away' for the fun of it?
6. Does {P} 'talk big' or claim to have more abilities or wealth than is true?
7. Does {P} show any other signs of feeling too good or being too happy?
1. Does {P} seem less spontaneous and less active than usual?
2. Is {P} less likely to initiate a conversation?
3. Is {P} less affectionate or lacking in emotions when compared to his/her usual self?
4. Does {P} contribute less to household chores?
5. Does {P} seem less interested in the activities and plans of others?
6. Has {P} lost interest in friends and family members?
7. Is {P} less enthusiastic about his/her usual interests?
8. Does {P} show any other signs that he/she doesn't care about doing new things?
1. Does {P} act impulsively without appearing to consider the consequences?
2. Does {P} talk to total strangers as if he/she knew them?
3. Does {P} say things to people that are insensitive or hurt their feelings?
4. Does {P} say crude things or make sexual remarks that they would not usually have said?
5. Does {P} talk openly about very personal or private matters not usually discussed in public?
6. Does {P} take liberties or touch or hug others in a way that is out of character for him/her?
7. Does {P} show any other signs of loss of control of his/her impulses?
1. Does {P} have a bad temper, flying 'off the handle' easily over little things?
2. Does {P} rapidly change moods from one to another, being fine one minute and angry the next?
3. Does {P} have sudden flashes of anger?
4. Is {P} impatient, having trouble coping with delays or waiting for planned activities?
6. Is {P} argumentative and difficult to get along with?
7. Does {P} show any other signs of irritability?
1. Does {P} pace around the house without apparent purpose?
2. Does {P} rummage around opening and unpacking drawers or closets?
3. Does {P} repeatedly put on and take off clothing?
4. Does {P} have repetitive activities or 'habits' that he/she performs over and over?
5. Does {P} engage in repetitive activities such as handling buttons, picking, wrapping string, etc?
6. Has {P} fidget excessively, seem unable to sit still, or bounce his/her feet or tap his/her fingers a lot?
7. Does {P} do any other activities over and over?
